'''Abu Ali Fana-Khusrau''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: ابو علی فنا-خسرو), was the son of the [[Buyid]] ruler [[Abu Kalijar]]. After the fall of the Buyid Empire in 1055, Abu Ali spent the rest of his life residing at Naubandajan in [[Fars Province|Fars]], where he became an honored figure among the [[Seljuq Empire|Seljuq]] sultans. He died in 1094, and was given an honorable funeral.
== Sources == * {{cite book | last = Frye | first = R.N. | authorlink = | chapter = The Saljuq and Mongol periods | title = The Cambridge History of Iran, Volume 5: The Iranian world | year = 1975 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location=Cambridge | url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=16yHq5v3QZAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | editor-first = R.N. | editor-last = Frye | isbn = 0-521-20093-8| pages=1-659}}
