{{Suicide sidebar}}
'''Suicide in Bhutan''' in recent years has become a notable phenomenon in the small [[Himalayas|Himalayan]] kingdom, which promotes [[Gross National Happiness]] as a government policy. As the [[Kingdom of Bhutan]] adheres to [[Tibetan Buddhism]] for its state religion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhutanmysticbliss.com/bhutan-travel/religion-of-bhutan.html|title=About Mystic Bliss Tours and Travel - Bhutan Travel, Bhutan Tours.|publisher=}}</ref> the mere discussion of suicide and the means of tackling it have been generally seen as socially [[taboo]] amongst most [[Bhutan]]ese.<ref>http://www.jdwnrh.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2011/10/Suicide.pdf{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
Under [[Bhutanese law]], the act of committing suicide is itself not illegal, but abetting a suicide is regarded as a crime.
Based on 2011 data, the official suicide rate of Bhutan was 16.2 per 100,000 people. This figure ranked the kingdom as the 20th-highest suicide rate [[List of countries by suicide rate|in the world]], and 6th highest in the [[Asia-Pacific]] region.<ref>worldlifeexpectancy.com [http://www.worldlifeexpectancy.com/bhutan-suicide Suicide in Bhutan]</ref> The number of recorded deaths has increased by around 50% for the years 2012 and 2013,<ref>thebhutanese.bt [http://www.thebhutanese.bt/rapidly-rising-suicide-rates-become-the-second-biggest-killer-after-road-accidents-in-bhutan Second Biggest Killer in Bhutan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103202047/http://www.thebhutanese.bt/rapidly-rising-suicide-rates-become-the-second-biggest-killer-after-road-accidents-in-bhutan/ |date=2013-11-03 }}</ref> which places the Himalayan Kingdom among the countries with the highest suicide rates in the world. Lack of job opportunities, the percentage of broken families, and a high rate of [[domestic violence]] are considered to be major contributing factors.
Autopsies are not done in Bhutan, and thus the actual suicide rate is likely to be higher than the official rate. Some suicides are reported as "accidental deaths".
In addition, the suicide rate has been widely discussed about [[Bhutanese refugees]] who live outside Bhutan, who tend to be of [[People of Nepal|Nepalese]] origin,<ref>Danielle Preiss ''[[The Atlantic]]'' [https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/04/bhutanese-refugees-are-killing-themselves-at-an-astonishing-rate/274959/ Bhutanese Refugees Are Killing Themselves at an Astonishing Rate] </ref> as [[unemployment]], lack of family ties and [[clinical depression|depression]] ensue.<ref>[[BBC News]] [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/8128227.stm Concern over Bhutan suicide rate]</ref>
